{{Infobox Institute |name = National Institute of Radiological Sciences |image_name = National_Institutes_for_Quantum_and_Radiological_Science_and_Technology.JPG |caption = Main gate |established = 1957 |head_label = President |head = Yoshiharu Yonekura, M.D., Ph.D. |president = |faculty = |staff = 800 (As of 2012) |budget = |endowment = |debt = |location = Chiba, Japan |address = 4-9-1 Anagawa, Inage-ku, Chiba-shi, Chiba 263-8555, Japan |website = {{official website|http://www.nirs.qst.go.jp/ENG/index.shtml}} }}
The {{nihongo|'''National Institute of Radiological Sciences'''|放射線医学総合研究所}} ('''NIRS''') is a [[radiation]] research institute in [[Japan]]. The NIRS was established in 1957 as the Japan's only one institute of [[radiology]]. The NIRS maintains various [[particle accelerator|ion accelerators]] in order to study the effects of radiation of the human body and medical uses of radiation.<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 22380179 | year = 2012 | author1 = Kitagawa | first1 = A | title = Status of ion sources at National Institute of Radiological Sciences | journal = Review of Scientific Instruments | volume = 83 | issue = 2 | pages = 02A332 | last2 = Fujita | first2 = T | last3 = Goto | first3 = A | last4 = Hattori | first4 = T | last5 = Hamano | first5 = T | last6 = Hojo | first6 = S | last7 = Honma | first7 = T | last8 = Imaseki | first8 = H | last9 = Katagiri | first9 = K | last10 = Muramatsu | first10 = M | last11 = Sakamoto | first11 = Y | last12 = Sekiguchi | first12 = M | last13 = Suda | first13 = M | last14 = Sugiura | first14 = A | last15 = Suya | first15 = N | doi = 10.1063/1.3670742 }}</ref>
The National Institute of Radiological Sciences hospital established in 1961 is a research hospital with a basic focus on [[radiation therapy]].<ref>[https://www.medical-excellence-japan.org/en/hospital/002/index.html Charged Particle Therapy Research Center Hospital, National Institute of Radiological Sciences]</ref> In 1993 the HIMAC (Heavy Ion Medical Accelerator in Chiba) of NIRS was launched, and in 1997 the Research Center for Charged Particle Therapy was opened as one of the leading medical centers using [[particle therapy|carbon ions]] are in operation.
On April 1, 2016, the [[Japan Atomic Energy Agency]] (JAEA) transferred some of its laboratories to the NIRS, and the NIRS body was renamed to the National Institutes for Quantum and Radiological Science and Technology (QST) which includes existing laboratories of the NIRS; the NIRS is currently a radiological research division of the QST.
